From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
Subject: [PATCH] Fix TMA shared memory alignment for sm_120 (Blackwell consumer)

`SharedMemoryAlignmentPlanner` previously enforced 1024-byte alignment on
TMA-touched shared-memory buffers only when the target is Hopper
(arch in [90, 100)).  Blackwell consumer GPUs (sm_120, e.g. RTX 5090) and
data-center Blackwell (sm_100) also support and require TMA, but the
planner falls back to 16-byte alignment for them.

`cp.async.bulk.tensor.{1..5}d.shared::cta.global.*` requires the
destination shared memory pointer to be 128-byte aligned.  When the
dynamic-smem arena begins with any small (e.g. 4-byte float) buffer, the
TMA buffers placed after it land at 16-byte (but not 128-byte) aligned
offsets, and the load raises `CUDA_ERROR_MISALIGNED_ADDRESS` on sm_120.

Hopper appeared to tolerate this misalignment in the wild
(possibly because of more permissive enforcement on sm_90 + the buffer
positions happening to be 128-aligned for most kernels); sm_120 strictly
enforces 128-byte alignment.

Use `TargetHasBulkCopy(target)` instead, which is true for any target with
TMA (arch >= 90), so sm_100, sm_120 and any future TMA-capable target get
the same strict alignment automatically.

Reproduces with the standalone TileLang script under "How to reproduce" in
the issue.

---
 src/transform/merge_shared_memory_allocations.cc | 2 +-
 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/src/transform/merge_shared_memory_allocations.cc b/src/transform/merge_shared_memory_allocations.cc
index f6f61b0..5bfac6b 100644
--- a/src/transform/merge_shared_memory_allocations.cc
+++ b/src/transform/merge_shared_memory_allocations.cc
@@ -390,7 +390,7 @@ private:
     if (scope == "shared" || scope == "shared.dyn") {
       auto target = Target::Current();
       ICHECK(target.defined()) << "Target is not defined";
-      const int alignment = TargetIsHopper(target) ? 1024 : 16;
+      const int alignment = TargetHasBulkCopy(target) ? 1024 : 16;
       shmem_alignment_map_[op] = alignment;
     }
   }
